      medications: [{ name: "Oral Vancomycin", type: "Glycopeptide Antibiotic", action: "Treats C. difficile colitis (poorly absorbed orally, acts locally in GI tract)", sideEffects: "Nausea, abdominal pain, taste disturbance", contra: "Known hypersensitivity", pearl: "Oral vancomycin is first-line for C. difficile; IV vancomycin does NOT reach the GI lumen and is ineffective for C. difficile." },{ name: "Mupirocin (Bactroban)", type: "Topical Antibiotic", action: "MRSA nasal decolonization by inhibiting bacterial protein synthesis", sideEffects: "Nasal irritation, headache", contra: "Hypersensitivity to mupirocin", pearl: "Apply intranasally BID x 5 days for MRSA decolonization; often paired with chlorhexidine bathing." }],
      pearls: ["C. difficile spores survive alcohol-based sanitizers; always use soap and water","Contact precautions are the MOST commonly used transmission-based precautions","Dedicate stethoscopes, BP cuffs, and thermometers to the patient's room","Educate visitors before entry; they must gown and glove too","Isolation can cause depression and anxiety; maintain therapeutic communication"],
      quiz: [{ question: "A nurse is caring for a patient with C. difficile infection. Which hand hygiene method is most appropriate?", options: ["Alcohol-based hand sanitizer for 20 seconds","Soap and water handwashing for at least 20 seconds","Either method is equally effective","Hand sanitizer followed by glove application"], correct: 1, rationale: "C. difficile forms spores that are resistant to alcohol-based sanitizers. Only mechanical friction with soap and water physically removes spores from the hands." },{ question: "Which PPE is required for contact precautions?", options: ["N95 respirator and gloves","Gown, gloves, and face shield","Gown and gloves","Gloves only"], correct: 2, rationale: "Contact precautions require gown and gloves upon room entry. N95 respirators are for airborne precautions, and face shields are for droplet precautions." },{ question: "A patient on contact precautions for MRSA needs a chest X-ray. What should the nurse do?", options: ["Remove precautions for transport since MRSA is on the skin","Apply a clean gown to the patient, notify receiving department, and clean transport equipment after","Cancel the X-ray until precautions are discontinued","Have the patient walk to radiology without PPE"], correct: 1, rationale: "The patient should wear a clean gown during transport, the receiving department must be notified to prepare, and all transport equipment must be cleaned after use to prevent transmission." }]
